  "safetyRules": [
    "Treat emergency pages as recognition and preparation support, not diagnosis, triage automation, or a substitute for local emergency services.",
    "Keep all emergency numbers, poison-service details, transport guidance, positioning, first aid, rescue medicine, oral treatment, and device instructions locally adaptable and clinical-review-required.",
    "Do not delay emergency care to repeat a measurement, search the app, complete a diary, or wait for symptoms to resolve.",
    "Do not advise driving when breathing, consciousness, vision, coordination, judgment, severe pain, or treatment effects may be impaired.",
    "Do not give food, drink, tablets, or oral glucose to a person who is unconscious, having a seizure, vomiting repeatedly, or unable to swallow safely.",
    "Do not recommend aspirin, extra blood-pressure medicine, extra insulin, rescue medicines, epinephrine, glucagon, or any other product unless the person is following a clinician-approved plan, trained device instructions, or local emergency guidance.",
    "Do not provide universal missed-dose, double-dose, stop, restart, withdrawal, overdose, poison, surgery, pregnancy, or adverse-event reporting instructions.",
    "Require exact product names, strengths, routes, last doses, labels, containers, lot numbers when relevant, allergies, diagnoses, pregnancy status, and symptom-onset time for medicine and supplement safety review.",
    "Keep severe allergy, anaphylaxis, stroke, heart attack, seizure, altered consciousness, bleeding, dehydration, glucose, blood-pressure, poisoning, self-harm, safeguarding, and pregnancy emergency wording clinical-review-required.",
    "Printed plans must state that they are educational planning aids and must not be used to delay emergency care or independently change treatment.",
    "Keep all app references local and editorial; do not display source URLs in the patient interface.",
    "Keep vaccine schedules, live-vaccine decisions, immune-testing thresholds, fever plans during immune suppression, neutropenia instructions, food-safety restrictions, antimicrobial treatment, and supplement dosing clinical-review-required."
  ],
